es to necessarily even check the checksums. There's<br />some real crap out there.<br /><br />Iirc, the common USB packet size is 512 bytes, so your corruption<br />pattern could match that "end of a packet" kind of rule (especially<br />with the header to specify where the write goes). I dunno. Hardware<br />problems can be a nasty nasty issue to debug.<br /><br />                            Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
